{"slug": "portent", "root": "portent", "category": "divination", "gloss": "a sign of things to come", "definition": "A *portent* is a sign, especially an ominous one — an unusual event in the natural world read as a warning of things to come. Unlike the arts of divination, which the diviner performs, a portent is a sign received: it is not sought through a method but noticed and interpreted where it appears.", "history": "Latin *portentum* comes from *portendere*, 'to foretell' — literally to stretch forward, so that the future reaches back to touch the present. Ancient and medieval writers read comets, monstrous births, and strange heavenly phenomena as portents; Isidore of Seville treated monsters as divine signs, usually a warning of catastrophe. As Keith Thomas describes, unusual happenings, or 'prodigies,' were taken as likely indications — portents — of judgements to come, a belief that lingered even as comets were absorbed into the new natural philosophy. Magic keeps the word for its omens and looming signs.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Thomas, Religion and the Decline of Magic", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Page, Magic in the Cloister", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. portent (Latin portendere)", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"lang": "Latin", "origin": "Latin portentum, from portendere 'to foretell' (por- + tendere 'to stretch')", "first": "early 15c.", "note": "A portent 'stretches forward' — the future reaching back to touch the present.", "hook": "An omen that reaches out of the future."}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 7, "oracle_total": 1, "in_flavor_cards": 7, "in_oracle_cards": 1, "name_match_count": 7, "by_variant": {"portent": 6, "portents": 2}, "first_year": 